</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,310,704,730]" box="[189,310,704,730]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,704,730]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,704,730]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1399,757,910]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
In most respects similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vallot" authorityYear="1836" box="[495,600,757,784]" class="Insecta" family="Adelgidae" genus="Adelges" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laricis">
<emphasis box="[495,600,757,784]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">A. laricis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Al. gallicolae: ant. III longer than IV; glands (including premarginal) developed, abundant wax wool produced. Holocyclic and dioecious, alternating between 
<taxonomicName box="[1278,1345,800,825]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Picea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1278,1345,800,825]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Picea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[189,253,842,867]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Larix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,253,842,867]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Larix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see also p. 25). Galls 
<quantity box="[533,650,841,868]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="10.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="5.0">5–15 mm</quantity>
, widely dispersed, usually singly on their branch, opening late June–September. Gallicolae emerge from late July to August; secreting abundant wax.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,492,955,981]" box="[189,492,955,981]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
